1
00:00:00,500 --> 00:00:01,190
Speaker 13: Hello everyone.

2
00:00:01,309 --> 00:00:05,630
My name is Kush Bonum, and I work
as a cloud architect focused on

3
00:00:05,750 --> 00:00:08,420
observability for cloud native systems.

4
00:00:08,870 --> 00:00:13,670
In this session, I want to talk about
a problem I see SRE teams face quite

5
00:00:13,730 --> 00:00:19,639
often as distributed systems scale, they
generate massive amounts of telemetry.

6
00:00:20,119 --> 00:00:24,035
At first glance, having motor
telemetry seems like a good thing.

7
00:00:24,865 --> 00:00:30,444
But when an incident actually occurs, the
real challenge is not collecting the data,

8
00:00:30,564 --> 00:00:33,115
but making sense of the collected data.

9
00:00:33,595 --> 00:00:39,415
And that's exactly why the central idea of
the talk is correlation over collection.

10
00:00:39,865 --> 00:00:44,650
Instead of trying to collect more and
more telemetry teams should focus on

11
00:00:44,790 --> 00:00:47,130
an intentional observability design.

12
00:00:47,980 --> 00:00:52,840
Adding the right context to existing
signals so engineers can connect

13
00:00:52,840 --> 00:00:55,245
the dots quickly during an incident.

14
00:00:55,745 --> 00:00:59,705
When we look at modern distributed
systems, they generate many

15
00:00:59,705 --> 00:01:01,265
different types of telemetry.

16
00:01:01,805 --> 00:01:05,345
You might have matrix from
infrastructure, application logs,

17
00:01:05,345 --> 00:01:10,685
distributed traces, deployment
signals, and multiple alerts set up.

18
00:01:10,985 --> 00:01:14,645
So in most cases, we actually
don't have a data problem.

19
00:01:15,095 --> 00:01:19,115
We already know how to collect
telemetry, what tools to use.

20
00:01:19,595 --> 00:01:21,605
The real challenge is clarity.

21
00:01:22,375 --> 00:01:28,045
Each of these signals is valuable on its
own, but they often exist in isolation.

22
00:01:28,615 --> 00:01:32,185
They don't automatically tell a
structured story about what is

23
00:01:32,185 --> 00:01:36,685
happening inside the system, and
we generally need more context.

24
00:01:37,195 --> 00:01:40,795
So when an incident occurs, all
of these signals compete for

25
00:01:40,855 --> 00:01:42,660
attention at the same moment.

26
00:01:43,355 --> 00:01:46,985
And the engineer investigating
the problem becomes the manual

27
00:01:46,985 --> 00:01:51,725
integration layer, trying to connect
the dots between the fragmented data.

28
00:01:52,535 --> 00:01:56,615
That's why the core issue
isn't the volume of telemetry.

29
00:01:57,065 --> 00:01:58,835
The real issue is clarity.

30
00:01:59,335 --> 00:02:04,255
Now let's look at what typically happens
when an incident actually begins.

31
00:02:04,585 --> 00:02:08,995
The investigation timeline often
starts with a user request, then

32
00:02:08,995 --> 00:02:11,245
something unusual may happen.

33
00:02:11,515 --> 00:02:13,345
For example, latency starts increasing.

34
00:02:13,845 --> 00:02:17,535
Soon after that, a monitoring
alert fires and the engineers

35
00:02:17,535 --> 00:02:19,245
start looking into this issue.

36
00:02:19,635 --> 00:02:23,355
But at this point, there
is an important gap.

37
00:02:23,805 --> 00:02:26,835
Many signals can tell us
that something is wrong.

38
00:02:26,955 --> 00:02:28,410
They show the symptoms of the problem.

39
00:02:28,910 --> 00:02:33,890
But very few signals immediately
explain why the problem is happening.

40
00:02:34,280 --> 00:02:38,870
So the first question an engineer
usually asks during an incident is

41
00:02:38,870 --> 00:02:44,120
not what happened because the alert
already tells us something is wrong.

42
00:02:44,510 --> 00:02:47,960
The real question is what changed data?

43
00:02:47,960 --> 00:02:50,435
A new version of the
service gets deployed.

44
00:02:51,380 --> 00:02:55,310
Did infrastructure, A performance
degrade or did an external

45
00:02:55,310 --> 00:02:56,750
dependency start failing?

46
00:02:57,200 --> 00:03:02,450
Without that context, the investigation
becomes slow, manual, and stressful

47
00:03:02,750 --> 00:03:08,720
because engineers have to search across
many signals to reconstruct the story.

48
00:03:09,220 --> 00:03:12,730
And this is also where the
distinction between monitoring and

49
00:03:12,730 --> 00:03:14,590
observability becomes important.

50
00:03:14,710 --> 00:03:16,600
So a quick recap of that.

51
00:03:17,110 --> 00:03:21,190
Monitoring focuses on detecting
known failure conditions.

52
00:03:21,280 --> 00:03:27,970
For example, we define thresholds such
as CPU usage above 90%, or request

53
00:03:28,085 --> 00:03:30,335
latency above 500 milliseconds.

54
00:03:30,970 --> 00:03:34,750
And when those thresholds are
crossed, an alert is triggered.

55
00:03:35,375 --> 00:03:38,015
These are what we call the known nos.

56
00:03:38,645 --> 00:03:42,095
We already know what unhealthy
behavior looks like, and we want to

57
00:03:42,095 --> 00:03:47,975
avoid that, so we configure alerts
to detect it, but distributed systems

58
00:03:48,185 --> 00:03:50,735
rarely fail, only in predictable ways.

59
00:03:51,605 --> 00:03:54,425
That's where observability
becomes important.

60
00:03:54,925 --> 00:03:59,875
Observability helps engineers deal
with the unknown unknowns, meaning the

61
00:03:59,875 --> 00:04:05,725
failures that we did not explicitly
anticipate when designing alerts instead

62
00:04:05,725 --> 00:04:09,415
of just telling us that something
is wrong, observability helps us

63
00:04:09,445 --> 00:04:12,805
investigate and explain systems behavior.

64
00:04:13,305 --> 00:04:17,985
Now, even when we understand what
observability means, it still may not

65
00:04:17,985 --> 00:04:21,405
help us if our telemetry lacks context.

66
00:04:21,855 --> 00:04:26,685
In most modern systems, we collect
many different signals, for example.

67
00:04:27,405 --> 00:04:33,015
We might see Matrix showing a latency
spike logs reporting a payment timeout

68
00:04:33,075 --> 00:04:39,465
error traces revealing a slow API span
and deployment data showing that a new

69
00:04:39,585 --> 00:04:41,865
version of the service was released.

70
00:04:42,345 --> 00:04:44,595
Each of these signals is valuable.

71
00:04:44,980 --> 00:04:49,810
They are important and should be
collected, but without a shared

72
00:04:49,810 --> 00:04:51,670
context linking them together.

73
00:04:51,760 --> 00:04:55,420
They cannot explain why the
incident actually occurred.

74
00:04:55,990 --> 00:04:59,410
The signals exist, but they don't
automatically tell the story of

75
00:04:59,410 --> 00:05:03,310
what happened, and this is why
the telemetry should not simply

76
00:05:03,400 --> 00:05:05,590
be collected in large volumes.

77
00:05:05,980 --> 00:05:10,450
Telemetry should be designed for
correlation so that engineers can

78
00:05:10,450 --> 00:05:12,580
connect signals across the system.

79
00:05:12,635 --> 00:05:17,165
And understand and reach the root
cause faster and more efficiently.

80
00:05:17,665 --> 00:05:22,255
To tackle that problem, I want to
introduce the layered observability model.

81
00:05:22,975 --> 00:05:27,175
Instead of organizing telemetry
by tools or signal types, this

82
00:05:27,175 --> 00:05:32,875
model organizes signals by the
investigation question they help answer.

83
00:05:33,475 --> 00:05:37,855
Each layer provides a different
piece of context during an incident.

84
00:05:38,485 --> 00:05:41,485
At layer one, we start
with application traces.

85
00:05:41,895 --> 00:05:45,555
The key question here is,
where is the failure occurring?

86
00:05:46,095 --> 00:05:51,165
Tracing helps us follow a request
across services and identify which

87
00:05:51,165 --> 00:05:53,535
component in the transaction is failing.

88
00:05:54,105 --> 00:05:58,095
At layer two, we look at
Kubernetes metrics and events to

89
00:05:58,185 --> 00:05:59,805
understand the platform health.

90
00:06:00,375 --> 00:06:02,840
Here the question becomes,
is the platform healthy?

91
00:06:03,340 --> 00:06:08,010
For example, we might look at things
like node resource pressure, pod

92
00:06:08,010 --> 00:06:09,840
restarts, or scheduling issues.

93
00:06:09,840 --> 00:06:15,090
Here at layer three, we examine
CICD telemetry to understand

94
00:06:15,090 --> 00:06:16,860
what recently changed.

95
00:06:17,400 --> 00:06:22,680
This could include deployments, version
updates, or pipeline events that may

96
00:06:22,680 --> 00:06:24,715
correlate with the start of the incident.

97
00:06:25,215 --> 00:06:30,165
By structuring telemetry in these
layers, engineers can move through an

98
00:06:30,165 --> 00:06:35,025
investigation systematically instead
of jumping randomly between signals.

99
00:06:35,525 --> 00:06:39,965
Now let's see how this layered
model actually appears in a

100
00:06:39,965 --> 00:06:44,465
real system using a sample cloud
native application architecture.

101
00:06:44,885 --> 00:06:49,385
So in this example, I have a detailed
microservices application, which is

102
00:06:49,385 --> 00:06:52,325
running on a managed Kubernetes cluster.

103
00:06:53,045 --> 00:06:58,445
A user interacting with this application
is shown on the left side and this

104
00:06:58,445 --> 00:07:03,640
user's request enter the application
through a load balancer and then moves

105
00:07:03,640 --> 00:07:08,470
on to interact with the web frontend
service, which is the first microservice.

106
00:07:08,800 --> 00:07:14,230
And the second is the API backend service,
which has couple of operations of its own.

107
00:07:14,740 --> 00:07:17,590
It then interacts with an
external database, which is

108
00:07:17,650 --> 00:07:19,330
also within the cloud platform.

109
00:07:20,090 --> 00:07:23,330
The telemetry collected from the
different components here, which are

110
00:07:23,330 --> 00:07:29,990
the application Kubernetes and the CICD
pipeline is done using a combination

111
00:07:30,020 --> 00:07:35,720
of open telemetry collector and cloud
native services, and they are posted

112
00:07:35,750 --> 00:07:41,570
into different backends focusing on
application monitoring, log analysis.

113
00:07:42,500 --> 00:07:43,700
Matrix monitoring.

114
00:07:44,300 --> 00:07:46,550
So open that metric collector here.

115
00:07:46,640 --> 00:07:51,890
Also do one more additional thing,
which is enriching the application

116
00:07:51,890 --> 00:07:53,960
traces with useful context.

117
00:07:54,380 --> 00:07:59,510
And this enriched telemetry is what
allows us to correlate signals across

118
00:07:59,510 --> 00:08:04,010
different layers of investigation as
what we will see in the coming slides.

119
00:08:04,510 --> 00:08:08,050
Let's focus on layer one,
which is application traces.

120
00:08:08,470 --> 00:08:11,620
When a user request enters a
system, the trace follows entire

121
00:08:11,620 --> 00:08:13,780
request path across the services.

122
00:08:13,840 --> 00:08:18,430
And in this example, the request has
moved through the web service, then

123
00:08:18,430 --> 00:08:23,690
the API Service and the API service
includes the payment operation, and

124
00:08:23,690 --> 00:08:25,940
finally the request reaches the database.

125
00:08:26,330 --> 00:08:30,979
Each span in the trace shows how
long that particular operation took,

126
00:08:31,369 --> 00:08:36,049
and by comparing the latency of
each span, our user can understand.

127
00:08:36,049 --> 00:08:41,179
We can understand that which component in
the transaction is slowing things down.

128
00:08:41,329 --> 00:08:46,550
Like in this case, payment service span
is the one which is significantly slower

129
00:08:46,550 --> 00:08:51,290
than the others' paths, and therefore
slowing down the entire transaction.

130
00:08:51,855 --> 00:08:56,115
So this is how races helps us
answer where is the failure

131
00:08:56,175 --> 00:08:57,885
occurring in the request part?

132
00:08:58,384 --> 00:09:02,984
Now that we have seen how traces
help us answer where the service

133
00:09:03,014 --> 00:09:07,964
is failing, the next step is to
determine whether the issue is

134
00:09:07,964 --> 00:09:10,244
coming from the application itself.

135
00:09:10,675 --> 00:09:15,714
Or from the platform it runs on, and
this is where layer two Kubernetes

136
00:09:15,714 --> 00:09:18,234
matrix and events come into picture.

137
00:09:18,925 --> 00:09:23,724
At this layer, we look at different
matrix, or we look at logs and

138
00:09:23,724 --> 00:09:28,885
events that define the health of the
Kubernetes platform, for example.

139
00:09:29,089 --> 00:09:34,699
Matrix can reveal node resource pressure,
such as CBU or memory exhaustion

140
00:09:34,699 --> 00:09:36,379
that might be affecting the workload.

141
00:09:36,829 --> 00:09:42,479
Kubernetes events could explain
situations such as p the pod lifecycle

142
00:09:42,479 --> 00:09:44,819
events like crash loop back off.

143
00:09:45,180 --> 00:09:49,020
And in addition, scheduling and
orchestration signals can tell us

144
00:09:49,020 --> 00:09:54,869
whether pods are failing to start
being rescheduled or encountering

145
00:09:54,930 --> 00:09:57,420
resource constraints within the cluster.

146
00:09:58,265 --> 00:10:03,335
These platform signals help answer the
second investigation question that is

147
00:10:03,335 --> 00:10:08,915
the platform healthy or is infrastructure
instability contributing to the failure?

148
00:10:09,415 --> 00:10:13,834
Now before we continue to further layers
and investigations, there's one important

149
00:10:13,834 --> 00:10:15,635
point that I would like to clarify.

150
00:10:15,635 --> 00:10:20,584
When working with Kubernetes in a cloud
environment, in managed Kubernetes

151
00:10:20,615 --> 00:10:24,785
platform's, responsibility for
different parts of the system is shared

152
00:10:24,785 --> 00:10:28,175
between cloud provider and the users.

153
00:10:28,625 --> 00:10:32,704
So at the top of the stack is the
control plane, which has components

154
00:10:32,704 --> 00:10:36,395
such as API server, et cd, and in most.

155
00:10:37,260 --> 00:10:38,969
Managed Kubernetes services.

156
00:10:39,000 --> 00:10:43,140
These components are operated and
maintained by the cloud provider, so

157
00:10:43,199 --> 00:10:49,980
it's good to just check that what all
goes into the cloud operated category.

158
00:10:50,040 --> 00:10:55,195
And you can contact a cloud provider
if anything goes wrong with those co.

159
00:10:55,435 --> 00:10:56,455
Components.

160
00:10:56,935 --> 00:11:01,345
The second and third category are related
to note operations and application

161
00:11:01,345 --> 00:11:06,985
workloads, which are generally
completely managed by the end user.

162
00:11:07,465 --> 00:11:10,910
So when you are working
with managed Kubernetes, do.

163
00:11:11,360 --> 00:11:14,720
Figure out the policies
of your cloud platform.

164
00:11:14,720 --> 00:11:20,570
Understand what all telemetry, such as the
matrix and logs are also made available

165
00:11:20,570 --> 00:11:25,690
by the cloud provider for the components
that they manage, so that you can take

166
00:11:25,690 --> 00:11:29,050
the right path when an incident occurs.

167
00:11:29,550 --> 00:11:31,800
Now let's move on to the
third layer of observability

168
00:11:32,520 --> 00:11:35,640
here, which is CICD telemetry.

169
00:11:36,150 --> 00:11:40,350
While traces and platform signals
help understand where a failure occurs

170
00:11:40,350 --> 00:11:45,390
and whether the platform is healthy,
CICD telemetry helps answer another

171
00:11:45,390 --> 00:11:47,460
critical question during incidents.

172
00:11:47,755 --> 00:11:55,195
What changed CICD systems record important
signals such as deployment events, version

173
00:11:55,195 --> 00:11:58,135
updates, and pipeline execution results.

174
00:11:58,855 --> 00:12:03,505
These signals capture the lifecycle
of an application change from

175
00:12:03,505 --> 00:12:08,545
commit to build to testing, and
finally deployment into production.

176
00:12:09,130 --> 00:12:13,900
When an incident occurs, these
records allow engineers to quickly

177
00:12:13,900 --> 00:12:19,420
check whether a new version of the
service was deployed, a configuration

178
00:12:19,420 --> 00:12:24,395
change was introduced, or a pipeline
failure occurred around the same time.

179
00:12:24,895 --> 00:12:29,335
By correlating incidents with
deployment telemetry teams can

180
00:12:29,335 --> 00:12:33,985
determine whether the issue is related
to a recent change in the system.

181
00:12:34,465 --> 00:12:38,095
This layer therefore provides
the change context needed to

182
00:12:38,095 --> 00:12:39,955
complete the investigation.

183
00:12:40,455 --> 00:12:43,095
Now let's look at a real trace example.

184
00:12:43,485 --> 00:12:49,095
This trace shows the sequence of
operations involved in a single request.

185
00:12:49,635 --> 00:12:53,265
Each row represents a span
which corresponds to a specific

186
00:12:53,265 --> 00:12:56,865
operation, such as verify inventory
status, our charge payment.

187
00:12:57,365 --> 00:13:00,650
And in this example I've
highlighted the span, which is the

188
00:13:00,830 --> 00:13:03,110
payment service operations span.

189
00:13:03,530 --> 00:13:04,625
And it clearly shows an.

190
00:13:05,170 --> 00:13:09,580
Error along with a higher latency
compared to the other paths.

191
00:13:10,280 --> 00:13:12,980
So from this trace, we
learned two important things.

192
00:13:12,980 --> 00:13:16,040
First, where the failure
occurred in the transaction.

193
00:13:16,100 --> 00:13:20,240
Second, which service is
responsible for the problem.

194
00:13:20,840 --> 00:13:25,520
At this point, the investigation
has already narrowed from the entire

195
00:13:25,520 --> 00:13:31,010
system to a single component, but we
still need more context to understand

196
00:13:31,010 --> 00:13:35,660
why that service is failing, and
that's why we move to our layer two.

197
00:13:36,500 --> 00:13:41,900
Now that we have identified the
failing span, we need a way to trace

198
00:13:41,900 --> 00:13:46,820
back to the infrastructure where
this request was exactly executed.

199
00:13:47,360 --> 00:13:51,980
The most effective way to achieve
this is by enriching application

200
00:13:52,070 --> 00:13:54,770
telemetry with Kubernetes metadata.

201
00:13:55,430 --> 00:14:00,530
In this example, we are looking at the
same payment service span, but in detail.

202
00:14:01,340 --> 00:14:05,930
Here the span has been enriched with
Kubernetes attributes such as the node

203
00:14:05,930 --> 00:14:11,840
and pod name and the pod IB address, which
also I have highlighted on the right side.

204
00:14:12,815 --> 00:14:17,165
These attributes allow us to quickly
identify which pod handled the request

205
00:14:17,435 --> 00:14:19,715
and which node it was running on.

206
00:14:20,225 --> 00:14:24,545
At this point, the investigation can
pivot from the application layer to

207
00:14:24,545 --> 00:14:29,225
the platform layer, and we can now
examine the relevant infrastructure

208
00:14:29,225 --> 00:14:35,955
signals such as if this about this
nodes resource usage, this pods, events,

209
00:14:36,015 --> 00:14:40,935
or scheduling activity to determine
if that is what is causing the issue.

210
00:14:41,435 --> 00:14:46,655
So this correlation steps allows
us to separate platform issues

211
00:14:46,715 --> 00:14:51,935
from application faults much faster
during incident investigations.

212
00:14:52,435 --> 00:14:57,145
Now let's look at a practical
example of how CICD telemetry

213
00:14:57,145 --> 00:14:59,215
helps explain incidents.

214
00:14:59,785 --> 00:15:05,005
Here we correlate the incident with the
deployment that introduced the change

215
00:15:05,070 --> 00:15:11,850
so we are looking at the details of the
same span and further down the span.

216
00:15:11,850 --> 00:15:16,650
Metadata also includes a service
version, which tells us exactly which.

217
00:15:16,835 --> 00:15:19,085
Release, handle this request.

218
00:15:19,745 --> 00:15:24,425
If the infrastructure appears healthy,
but errors begin after a new deployment,

219
00:15:24,815 --> 00:15:29,285
we can immediately connect the incident
to that specific version of the service.

220
00:15:29,345 --> 00:15:35,645
And having that metadata in the span
quickly helps us in knowing that which

221
00:15:35,645 --> 00:15:38,235
serv service version we have to look at.

222
00:15:39,195 --> 00:15:44,835
The span also includes the error
message, which is captured due to the

223
00:15:44,925 --> 00:15:50,955
instrumentation of the application code,
and this helps us see exact failure

224
00:15:51,225 --> 00:15:55,545
reason returned by the application
by combining deployment metadata.

225
00:15:55,905 --> 00:16:02,085
With SPAN context, we can quickly identify
which change introduced the issue.

226
00:16:02,585 --> 00:16:07,745
Now when these three layers work
together, telemetry stops being

227
00:16:07,805 --> 00:16:12,575
just a collection of signals and
instead becomes structured evidence.

228
00:16:12,965 --> 00:16:16,655
First traces identify the specific
service and operation where the

229
00:16:16,655 --> 00:16:18,935
failure occurs within a transaction.

230
00:16:19,305 --> 00:16:24,315
Second platform signals help determine
whether infrastructure, conditions, such

231
00:16:24,315 --> 00:16:29,985
as node pressure, PO restarts, or resource
limits contributed to the problem.

232
00:16:30,495 --> 00:16:34,635
Third, deployment Elementary
provides a change context, allowing

233
00:16:34,695 --> 00:16:39,585
engineers to see whether a recent
version update or the configuration

234
00:16:39,585 --> 00:16:41,950
